<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-12T00:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-12T00:36:00-05:00" n="1257" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1257">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.2311/35.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-11T23:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 11—11 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My telegram of February 6, 6 p.m., and your February 9. Considering the
                            embarrassment with reference to the passage of the troops, the Mexican
                            Government states that it will forego availing itself of the permission
                            granted by the United States. Acting upon the authority granted in the
                            Department’s telegram February 8, 11 a.m., Mexican Government had
                            submitted a request to the Mexican Senate to be permitted to transport
                            troops out of Mexico territory. Mexican Government deems it inadvisable
                            to withdraw from the Senate this request. The action taken will have no
                            significance, but circumstances may arise under which Mexican Government
                            will renew its request.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>